1353":3,"1354":3,"1355":3,"1356":3,"1357":2,"1358":2,"1359":3,"1360":3,"1361":3,"1362":3,"1363":3,"1364":3,"1365":3,"1366":3,"1367":3,"1368":3,"1369":3,"1370":3,"1371":3,"1372":3,"1373":3,"1374":3,"1375":3,"1376":3,"1377":3,"1378":3,"1379":3,"1380":3,"1381":3,"1382":3,"1383":3,"1384":3,"1385":3,"1386":3,"1387":3,"1388":3,"1389":3,"1390":3,"1391":3,"1392":3,"1393":3,"1394":3,"1395":3,"1396":3,"1397":3,"1398":3,"1399":3,"1400":3,"1401":3,"1402":3,"1403":3,"1404":3,"1405":3,"1406":3,"1407":3,"1408":3,"1409":3,"1410":3,"1411":3,"1412":3,"1413":3,"1414":3,"1415":3,"1416":3,"1417":3,"1418":3,"1419":3,"1420":3,"1421":2,"1422":2,"1423":3,"1424":3,"1425":3,"1426":3,"1427":3,"1428":2,"1429":2,"1430":2,"1431":3,"1432":3,"1433":3,"1434":3,"1435":3,"1436":3,"1437":3,"1438":3,"1439":3,"1440":3,"1441":3,"1442":3,"1443":3,"1444":3,"1445":3,"1446":3,"1447":3,"1448":3,"1449":3,"1450":3,"1451":3,"1452":3,"1453":3,"1454":3,"1455":3,"1456":3,"1457":3,"1458":3,"1459":3,"1460":3,"1461":3,"1462":3,"1463":3}}},"docs":{"docs":{"1":{"id":"/","page_id":"/","type":"page","content":"What is Runyard","breadcrumbs":["Docs"],"tags":[],"url":"/"},"2":{"id":"/-0","page_id":"/","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/","content":"A self-hosted control plane for agent runs — workflows in, durable runs, logs, artifacts, and approvals out."},"3":{"id":"/-1","page_id":"/","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"4":{"id":"/-2","page_id":"/","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/","content":"Runyard is a self-hosted control plane for agent runs. Agents and humans trigger workflows over MCP, the CLI, the HTTP API, or the web app; runners execute those workflows with the Smithers engine; and the Hub stores the durable record of everything that happened — runs, logs, events, artifacts, approvals, and knowledge. A run started from a chat agent, a cron schedule, or a terminal all leaves the same auditable trail in the same place."},"5":{"id":"/-3","page_id":"/","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/","content":"Runyard is designed as one private deployment per company. Your Hub holds your workflow catalog, your secrets, your runners, and your history; nothing about your deployment is published to a shared service, and the only outbound call the Hub makes is a passive read of the public GitHub Releases API to check for updates. Operators, teammates, and their agents all authenticate to the same Hub with scoped access tokens."},"6":{"id":"/-4","page_id":"/","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/","content":"Runyard is API-first by construction. Every HTTP route the Hub serves is declared in a single API surface registry; the OpenAPI document is generated from it and the MCP tool list is parity-tested against it. The web app is an ordinary API client with no privileged endpoints — anything it can show or do is equally available over the API and MCP, so a third-party client built on those surfaces loses nothing."},"7":{"id":"/-5","page_id":"/","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/#next-steps","content":"<Card title=\"Quickstart\" href=\"./quickstart\" description=\"Install the Hub, start a runner, and run your first workflow.\" />"},"8":{"id":"/-6","page_id":"/","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/#next-steps","content":"<Card title=\"Concepts\" href=\"./concepts\" description=\"Workflows, runs, runners, approvals, and the Hub's durable record.\" />"},"9":{"id":"/-7","page_id":"/","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/#next-steps","content":"<Card title=\"HTTP API\" href=\"./guides/api\" description=\"Drive Runyard from any language with bearer-token auth and openapi.json.\" />"},"10":{"id":"/-8","page_id":"/","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/#next-steps","content":"<Card title=\"MCP\" href=\"./guides/mcp\" description=\"Connect AI agents to your Hub with the runyard-mcp server.\" />"},"11":{"id":"/quickstart","page_id":"/quickstart","type":"page","content":"Quickstart","breadcrumbs":["Docs"],"tags":[],"url":"/quickstart"},"12":{"id":"/quickstart-0","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart","content":"Install the Hub, sign in with the bootstrap token, start a runner, and run the hello workflow."},"13":{"id":"/quickstart-1","page_id":"/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/quickstart#1-install-the-hub","content":"1\\. Install the Hub"},"14":{"id":"/quickstart-2","page_id":"/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/quickstart#2-sign-in-with-the-bootstrap-token","content":"2\\. Sign in with the bootstrap token"},"15":{"id":"/quickstart-3","page_id":"/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/quickstart#3-install-the-cli-and-log-in","content":"3\\. Install the CLI and log in"},"16":{"id":"/quickstart-4","page_id":"/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/quickstart#4-start-a-runner","content":"4\\. Start a runner"},"17":{"id":"/quickstart-5","page_id":"/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/quickstart#5-run-the-hello-workflow","content":"5\\. Run the hello workflow"},"18":{"id":"/quickstart-6","page_id":"/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/quickstart#6-watch-the-run-and-read-the-results","content":"6\\. Watch the run and read the results"},"19":{"id":"/quickstart-7","page_id":"/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Where to go next"},"20":{"id":"/quickstart-8","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart","content":"This page takes you from a fresh Linux box to a completed workflow run with logs and artifacts in the Hub."},"21":{"id":"/quickstart-9","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#1-install-the-hub","content":"The repository's install script is a one-command, idempotent bootstrap. It installs Node 22 and pnpm if needed, clones Runyard at the latest release tag (default `/opt/runyard`), generates an env file with a `SECRETS_ENC_KEY` and session secret, creates the data directory, and installs systemd units for the Hub and a runner:"},"22":{"id":"/quickstart-10","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#1-install-the-hub","content":"Verify the Hub is up:"},"23":{"id":"/quickstart-11","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#1-install-the-hub","content":"The script never prints secrets, never applies updates automatically, and prints a Caddy reverse-proxy snippet if you want TLS in front (recommended for anything non-local — see the security guide)."},"24":{"id":"/quickstart-12","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#2-sign-in-with-the-bootstrap-token","content":"On first boot the Hub writes a full-admin bootstrap token to `bootstrap-token.txt` in its data directory (with the default install, `/opt/runyard/data/bootstrap-token.txt`, mode 600)."},"25":{"id":"/quickstart-13","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#2-sign-in-with-the-bootstrap-token","content":"Open the web app at your Hub URL (for example `https://hub.example.com`) and paste the bootstrap token into the sign-in form. The browser session carries exactly the token's scopes — the bootstrap token is admin, so you can now mint narrower tokens for everything else from the Connect tab."},"26":{"id":"/quickstart-14","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#3-install-the-cli-and-log-in","content":"Each deployment serves its own CLI install script:"},"27":{"id":"/quickstart-15","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#3-install-the-cli-and-log-in","content":"It installs the `runyard` and `runyard-mcp` commands into `~/.local/bin` and prompts for an access token. You can also log in later:"},"28":{"id":"/quickstart-16","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#4-start-a-runner","content":"Runners execute workflows with the Smithers engine, so a runner host needs `bun`, `smithers`, and at least one authenticated agent CLI (`claude`, `codex`, or `pi`) on its PATH."},"29":{"id":"/quickstart-17","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#4-start-a-runner","content":"If you used the Hub install script, a `runyard-runner` systemd unit is already installed and idling. Mint a runner-scoped token, put it in `/etc/runyard/runner.env` as `RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN=...`, then:"},"30":{"id":"/quickstart-18","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#4-start-a-runner","content":"To run an ad-hoc runner on any other machine (for example your laptop, for `local` execution):"},"31":{"id":"/quickstart-19","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#4-start-a-runner","content":"`runner setup` checks prerequisites and scaffolds the Smithers workspace the runner executes in. Confirm the runner is online:"},"32":{"id":"/quickstart-20","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#5-run-the-hello-workflow","content":"`hello` is a minimal seeded workflow that proves end-to-end execution: it asks the runner's Claude CLI for one sentence and returns structured output."},"33":{"id":"/quickstart-21","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#5-run-the-hello-workflow","content":"Web: open **Workflows**, pick &#x2A;*Hello (Smithers proof)**, fill in `topic`, and click Run."},"34":{"id":"/quickstart-22","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#5-run-the-hello-workflow","content":"CLI:"},"35":{"id":"/quickstart-23","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#5-run-the-hello-workflow","content":"MCP (from any connected agent):"},"36":{"id":"/quickstart-24","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#6-watch-the-run-and-read-the-results","content":"The same data lives at `GET /api/runs/{id}`, `/api/runs/{id}/timeline`, `/api/runs/{id}/logs`, and `/api/runs/{id}/artifacts`, and in the web run page — the Hub is the source of truth even when execution happened on a local runner."},"37":{"id":"/quickstart-25","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Authoring workflows — create your own workflows over the API or MCP."},"38":{"id":"/quickstart-26","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Approvals — put human checkpoints in front of dangerous work."},"39":{"id":"/quickstart-27","page_id":"/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Agent consumers — point AI agents at your Hub."},"40":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","type":"page","content":"Agents, Skills & Knowledge","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge"},"41":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-0","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","content":"The shared catalog of reusable agent roles, skills, and knowledge resources that workflows reference."},"42":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-1","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#the-three-catalogs","content":"The three catalogs"},"43":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-2","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#how-workflows-reference-them","content":"How workflows reference them"},"44":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-3","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#who-can-edit","content":"Who can edit"},"45":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-4","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#api--mcp","content":"API & MCP"},"46":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-5","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","content":"Alongside workflows, the Hub maintains a shared catalog of reusable building blocks. They live in the database, are readable by any authenticated token, and are edited only by admins — so every workflow on the Hub draws from the same curated set."},"47":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-6","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#the-three-catalogs","content":"Catalog"},"48":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-7","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#the-three-catalogs","content":"What it is"},"49":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-8","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#the-three-catalogs","content":"**Agents**"},"50":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-9","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#the-three-catalogs","content":"Reusable agent *roles*: a slug, name, description, instructions, a tool list, linked skill slugs, and tags. A role captures \"how this kind of agent should behave\" once, instead of restating it per workflow."},"51":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-10","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#the-three-catalogs","content":"**Skills**"},"52":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-11","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#the-three-catalogs","content":"Named, versioned instruction bodies (a slug, description, and body text) that agents and workflows can pull in by slug."},"53":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-12","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#the-three-catalogs","content":"**Knowledge**"},"54":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-13","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#the-three-catalogs","content":"Reference resources — documents or links with a type, body/URL, and tags — searchable with `?q=` / `search_knowledge`."},"55":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-14","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#the-three-catalogs","content":"All three are versioned and can be individually enabled/disabled."},"56":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-15","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#how-workflows-reference-them","content":"A workflow definition declares `requiredAgents` and `requiredSkills` as lists of catalog slugs; `describe_workflow` reports them alongside the schemas so a caller can see what a workflow depends on before running it. Workflow package exports record these requirements, and import preview reports whether the target Hub satisfies them."},"57":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-16","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#who-can-edit","content":"Reading any catalog requires only an authenticated token. Creating and updating entries requires the `admin` scope — the catalogs are part of the Hub's trusted configuration, like secrets and hook profiles."},"58":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-17","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge#who-can-edit","content":"In the web app the three catalogs share one section with deep links `#agents/agents`, `#agents/skills`, and `#agents/knowledge` (see Deep links)."},"59":{"id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge-18","page_id":"/concepts/agents-skills-knowledge","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/co