oped access token (admins issue them from the Connect tab or `POST /api/tokens`). Agents typically need `api` and/or `mcp` — nothing more. Send it as `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on every HTTP call, or configure it for the MCP server. Never ask for or expect the bootstrap/admin token."],[1257,"Assistant"],[679,"Attach runs three ways:"],[936,"Audit log (admin)"],[805,"Auth"],[799,"Auth expectations"],[833,"Authenticate, discover, and drive workflow runs over the Runyard Hub's HTTP API."],[834,"Authentication"],[1421,"Authoring workflows"],[37,"Authoring workflows — create your own workflows over the API or MCP."],[101,"Autonomous recovery gave up; a human records how to proceed."],[1200,"Back this directory up. The runner workspace, by contrast, is disposable\nscratch space — outputs and event traces are uploaded to the Hub as artifacts."],[565,"Bearer-token authentication, the scope vocabulary and presets (including read-only), the bootstrap token, and how browser and Telegram sessions work."],[450,"Before anything is enqueued, Runyard can run a **deterministic preflight**: schema checks on required input fields, runner/tag availability, secret presence, hook eligibility, and workflow source resolution. The result is `ready`, `needs_input` (with `questions[]` the caller can answer), or `blocked` (with `blockers[]` only an operator can fix), plus warnings, suggested defaults, and a `nextAction` hint."],[1165,"Bind address (default `127.0.0.1`)"],[189,"Board + lanes with per-lane ticket counts + the decorated work items in scope."],[150,"Boards"],[707,"Body: `{ runId }`."],[710,"Body: `{ runId }`."],[568,"Bootstrap token"],[997,"Bot setup"],[1430,"Both operations require an admin-scoped token."],[633,"Browser session bootstrap (rate-limited)."],[569,"Browser sessions"],[320,"Budgets"],[339,"Budgets are hard stops, not advisories:"],[795,"Building agents on Runyard"],[1289,"Builds and pushes GHCR `hub` and `runner` container images behind the same two gates, and records both image digests as a release artifact."],[119,"By default a card is blocking: nothing happens until someone decides. Supplying `timeoutMs` or `timeoutAt` at creation makes it a **timed approval**:"],[383,"By default the runner executes workflows directly on its host. Setting `RUNNER_SANDBOX=bubblewrap` on the runner wraps each workflow *launch* in a generated Bubblewrap (`bwrap`) sandbox: the run's workspace is the only writable mount (bound at the same path inside and out), system directories are bound read-only, and the child gets a fresh workspace-local `HOME` — the host home directory, with its keys and credentials, is never mounted. Polling and control commands stay outside the sandbox. Installing `bwrap` is the deployer's responsibility; the runner verifies at startup that the sandbox actually works before claiming runs."],[919,"Cancel; re-queue with same/edited input; merge a successful isolated run into its target branch"],[179,"Cancelling is already an operator act."],[667,"Cannot progress without a specific intervention (`blockedReason` says which)."],[869,"Canonical"],[369,"Capacity and pool"],[321,"Capture paths: what is metered today"],[1013,"Cards are posted to the configured chat with inline buttons (see below)."],[1060,"Cards can deep-link into the Hub as a Telegram WebApp. `POST /api/auth/telegram-webapp` exchanges the WebApp's signed init data for a browser session that is limited to the `approvals` scope — a Telegram identity can review and resolve approval cards, and nothing else. Full app access always requires a real access token."],[47,"Catalog"],[1253,"Catalog"],[1440,"Catalog grouping (for example `Examples`, `Operations`)."],[1050,"Chat (group or DM) where approval cards are posted."],[1381,"Check run diagnostics; fix workflow config or runner setup."],[1269,"CI pipeline"],[423,"Claimed by a runner, not yet started."],[1149,"claims runs and executes them; workspace volume at `/workspace`"],[1373,"Class"],[639,"Clears the session cookie."],[1008,"CLI"],[1061,"CLI"],[1301,"CLI"],[990,"CLI guide — the same API from your terminal"],[34,"CLI:"],[196,"CLI: `runyard board list`, `runyard board show <slug>` (lanes with counts and tickets), `runyard board create --slug … --title …`, `runyard board update <slug> …`."],[334,"CLI: `runyard usage` (fleet rollup) and `runyard usage <runId>` (one run's detail)."],[714,"CLI: `runyard work` (board list), `runyard work-item show|create|update|link|unlink`, `runyard flow <runId>`, and `runyard run <workflow> --work-item <id>`."],[1330,"Client install assets."],[675,"Closed historical item (hidden from lists by default)."],[1052,"Comma-separated Telegram user ids allowed to resolve approvals."],[148,"Comment describes the requested changes."],[1370,"Common causes: the runner unit is idling because `RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN` is empty or revoked; the runner's tags do not include what the workflow requires (`requiredRunnerTags`, for example `smithers`); or the run asked for `--where local` and only `vps` runners are registered. Running `runyard preflight <workflow>` before enqueueing catches `no_matching_runner` up front."],[298,"Concepts"],[1116,"Confidential VMs (dstack / Intel TDX)"],[673,"Confirmed to satisfy the original ask."],[1204,"Connect AI agents to a Runyard Hub with the runyard-mcp stdio server and its 87-tool surface."],[1064,"Connecting to a Hub"],[302,"Control"],[1147,"control plane + web UI + embedded datastore (HTTP on `PORT`, default 8080 in-container)"],[255,"Copy verified artifacts to a configured target root (optionally with a public URL base)."],[350,"Coverage"],[958,"Create + preflight a draft: `{workflow, input, executionMode}` → `201` with status `ready` / `needs_input` / `blocked` and open questions"],[1044,"Create a bot with Telegram's BotFather, then configure the Hub through environment variables (values belong in your env file or secret store — never in code or docs):"],[947,"Create a card: `{title, description, runId?, ask, timeoutMs?/timeo