un's lifecycle endpoints (`start`, `events`, `complete`, `fail`, artifact upload) only accept the runner that owns the run, or an admin. One compromised runner token cannot report on, or interfere with, another runner's work."],[356,"Runner-observed engine telemetry"],[1186,"Runner-scoped access token minted on the Hub"],[1180,"Runner:"],[365,"Runners"],[1239,"Runners"],[378,"Runners advertise **tags** (for example `local` on a workstation, `vps` on a shared remote pool). Two things match runs to runners:"],[456,"Runners append structured **events** as the run progresses; `GET /api/runs/{id}/events/stream` serves them live over SSE and `GET /api/runs/{id}/timeline` merges status transitions, events, and artifacts into one ascending feed (with `since`/`limit` paging). Log lines are at `/logs`, a condensed log summary and diagnostics at `/diagnostics`, and uploaded **artifacts** (outputs, traces, files) at `/artifacts`, downloadable by artifact id."],[1349,"Runners can execute workflow processes inside a bubblewrap sandbox (`RUNNER_SANDBOX=bubblewrap`), and the repo ships a narrow AppArmor profile (`deploy/apparmor/install.sh`) that grants unprivileged user-namespace creation to bwrap on Ubuntu 24.04+ kernels that restrict it. This is not on faith: CI runs a `sandbox-smoke` job on every push that installs bubblewrap, loads the profile through the same operator install script, and runs the sandbox suites with `RUNYARD_REQUIRE_BWRAP=1` so the real-bwrap smoke test fails instead of silently skipping if the path regresses."],[28,"Runners execute workflows with the Smithers engine, so a runner host needs `bun`, `smithers`, and at least one authenticated agent CLI (`claude`, `codex`, or `pi`) on its PATH."],[373,"Runners speak a small machine protocol authenticated with **runner-scoped tokens** (see Tokens & scopes):"],[389,"Runners, heartbeat state, capacity, slots, pool summary."],[1227,"Running"],[794,"Running a workflow (`POST /api/workflows/{id}/run`, `run_workflow`) and preflighting it are covered on the Runs page."],[1113,"Running from source"],[403,"Runs"],[1229,"Runs (observe)"],[444,"Runs also meter the model calls they consume: per-call usage records stream as `run.usage` events and aggregate onto the run as `usage` (`totalTokens`, `costMicros`, `byModel`, ...), and run creation accepts an optional `budget: { maxTokens?, maxCostMicros? }` hard ceiling. Budgeted runs additionally carry a computed `budgetStatus` (spent vs limit, remaining, percent used, `nearLimit` at 80%) in list and detail payloads. See Usage metering & budgets for the data model, the fleet rollup (`GET /api/usage/summary`), the metering gateway, and budget enforcement."],[1410,"Runs failing with provider auth errors usually mean the runner's `codex`/`claude` CLI login lapsed. On hosts with `REAUTH_ENABLED=1`, an admin can trigger re-auth from the web app (runner card → Re-auth): the Hub surfaces a verification URL and user code, and never token material. Otherwise, log in on the runner host directly (`codex login`, `claude setup-token`)."],[153,"Runs move tickets"],[354,"Runs that select `metering: \"gateway\"` with the pi harness (`piModel`, `piBaseUrl`, `piApiKeyEnv`)"],[1121,"Runyard is a self-hosted control plane for agent runs. A deployment has a small,\nfixed shape:"],[4,"Runyard is a self-hosted control plane for agent runs. Agents and humans trigger workflows over MCP, the CLI, the HTTP API, or the web app; runners execute those workflows with the Smithers engine; and the Hub stores the durable record of everything that happened — runs, logs, events, artifacts, approvals, and knowledge. A run started from a chat agent, a cron schedule, or a terminal all leaves the same auditable trail in the same place."],[304,"Runyard is a self-hosted control plane for agent runs. You install **workflows** into a catalog, start **runs** of those workflows from the API, MCP, web app, or a **schedule**, and **runners** claim and execute them. The durable company asks those runs work on are **work items** — tickets on the Work board. Anything that needs a human decision surfaces as an **approval** card, sensitive values live in the encrypted **secrets** store, and optional side effects after a run are handled by admin-defined **hooks**. Access is governed by scoped **tokens**, and every page in the Hub is a shareable **deep link**."],[6,"Runyard is API-first by construction. Every HTTP route the Hub serves is declared in a single API surface registry; the OpenAPI document is generated from it and the MCP tool list is parity-tested against it. The web app is an ordinary API client with no privileged endpoints — anything it can show or do is equally available over the API and MCP, so a third-party client built on those surfaces loses nothing."],[5,"Runyard is designed as one private deployment per company. Your Hub holds your workflow catalog, your secrets, your runners, and your history; nothing about your deployment is published to a shared service, and the only outbound call the Hub makes is a passive read of the public GitHub Releases API to check for updates. Operators, teammates, and their agents all authenticate to the same Hub with scoped access tokens."],[1315,"Runyard is one private deployment per company, and the security model follows from that: a small, deliberate unauthenticated surface; scoped bearer tokens for everything else; secrets encrypted at rest and never echoed; and approval gates in front of dangerous work."],[542,"Runyard keeps reusable credentials (API keys, deploy tokens) in an **encrypted secret store** on the Hub. Values are encrypted at rest, and the API is deliberately one-way: you can list secret *names and metadata*, set a value, and delete one — **values are never returned** by any list or read endpoint, to any scope."],[1143,"Runyard publishes two environment-agnostic images to GHCR:"],[1273,"Runyard releases are semver git tags (`vX.Y.Z`). The version in `package.json` is the single source of truth and flows to `/api/version`, the OpenAPI document, the CLI, and the update checker."],[1304,"Runyard ships a repo-agnostic `docs-update` workflow that keeps documentation honest against each release. When a release is published, a GitHub Actions step triggers it on the project's own Hub through an authenticated workflow endpoint (`release-docs-update`); the workflow inspects only the git diff between the previous and new release tags — never the whole repository — and reports proposed documentation updates. In its opt-in `apply` mode it edits docs in an isolated worktree branch instead, and that branch reaches the target branch only through a human-approved run promotion. The repository, docs path, docs framework, and file-selection rules are all workflow inputs, so any repo can adopt it."],[803,"Runyard treats agents as first-class API consumers. This page covers how a client discovers what a Hub can do, what it may rely on, and how to be a good citizen."],[499,"Runyard uses standard **5-field cron** (`minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week`) with ranges (`a-b`), lists (`a,b,c`), steps (`*/n`, `a-b/n`), month/weekday names (`jan..dec`, `sun..sat`), and the aliases `@yearly`, `@monthly`, `@weekly`, `@daily`, `@hourly`. There is no seconds field — the Hub ticks at minute granularity."],[1282,"Same"],[370,"Sandboxing"],[491,"Schedules"],[1233,"Schedules"],[232,"Schedules / one schedule."],[575,"Scope"],[847,"Scope"],[1333,"Scope"],[566,"Scopes"],[592,"Scopes"],[1308,"Scopes"],[1173,"Secret for browser session cookies. Required in production; in dev a generated value is persisted to the data dir"],[543,"Secret names are env-var-safe identifiers, because that is exactly how they are delivered. The whole feature is gated on the store being enabled (an encryption key configured on the Hub); when it is not, secret-dependent runs and hooks report that configuration is required instead of failing obscurely."],[1054,"Secret Telegram echoes back so the Hub can verify