],[416,"Status"],[654,"Status"],[967,"Status"],[91,"Status and resolution"],[676,"Status moves happen two ways, both recorded in ticket history as `work_item.status_changed` events (alongside run link/unlink events and field edits): explicit `PATCH`es by a human or agent, and automatic moves by linked runs where the mapping is reliable — a run going live puts the ticket in `running`, a held run parks it in `waiting`, a succeeded run sends it to `review`, a failed run parks it in `blocked` with a reason. Automated moves are attributed to the run (`actor: \"run:run_…\"`); see Boards for the full mapping."],[431,"Stopped by an operator or a rejected approval — a human \"no\" is a decision, not a failure."],[549,"Stored secret values are additionally scrubbed from run output and artifacts before they are persisted."],[1414,"Structured diagnosis + log summary for a run (`get_run_diagnostics`)."],[915,"Structured events, log lines, diagnostics + log summary"],[1344,"Superscope: satisfies every scope requirement and gates all mutation of workflows, secrets, tokens, schedules, hooks, and updates."],[1213,"Supported `--client` values: `claude-code`, `claude-desktop`, `codex`,\n`cursor`, `windsurf`, `gemini`, `vscode`. Each writes the appropriate config\nfile (for example `.mcp.json` for Claude Code, `~/.codex/config.toml` for\nCodex, `.vscode/mcp.json` for VS Code) and prints how to activate it."],[804,"Surface"],[1002,"Surface"],[1293,"Surface"],[1411,"Surface"],[1114,"systemd"],[734,"Tags a runner must advertise to be assigned a run."],[1446,"Tags a runner must advertise to claim runs (for example `[\"smithers\"]`)."],[368,"Tags and execution modes"],[142,"Takes an approval id, not a run id."],[1086,"Target a specific runner location tag"],[1012,"Telegram"],[996,"Telegram integration"],[1365,"Telegram not delivering"],[1000,"Telegram WebApp login"],[570,"Telegram WebApp sessions"],[433,"Terminal failure; see failure classes below."],[1372,"Terminal failures carry a class so you know whether to fix input, config, or infrastructure:"],[332,"Terminal response-endpoint payloads — `usage`, `budget`, and `budgetStop` fields, so delegated callers can bill or cap against real consumption."],[434,"Terminal states are final: late reports racing a terminal state are absorbed idempotently rather than overwriting the first decision."],[170,"The \"Needs decision\" lane."],[1005,"The **Approvals** view lists pending cards with their ask, consequences, and buttons."],[1217,"The `--remote <name>` argument, resolved against the saved remotes in\n`~/.runyard/config.json` (written by `runyard login`)"],[977,"The `422`/`409` bodies are returned by `run` with `negotiate: true` and by\ndraft `submit`; they are structured responses, not opaque failures — answer the\nquestions and retry."],[1073,"The `runyard` CLI is a thin client of the Hub's HTTP API. It talks\nto one or more Hubs (\"remotes\"), starts and tails workflow runs, resolves\napprovals, and can set up and start a runner on the local machine."],[490,"The `start`/`complete`/`fail`/event-append and artifact-upload endpoints under `/api/runs/{id}` are the runner protocol (runner-scoped tokens, run ownership enforced) — see Runners."],[1389,"The agent's output failed schema validation."],[127,"The API exposes these as `whatHappensIfApproved` / `whatHappensIfRejected` / `whatHappensIfChangesRequested` / `whatHappensIfIgnored` in each card's `context`, alongside the ask, the linked run, and deep links."],[240,"The API hands these links back so agents and integrations can point humans at the right screen without building URLs themselves:"],[798,"The API-first guarantee"],[90,"The ask contract"],[1142,"The bootstrap script installs these for you, retargeted to your install\ndirectory, env-file location, and node binary. Secrets live in the\n`EnvironmentFile`s (mode `0600`), never in the units."],[1048,"The bot's API token."],[267,"The caller selects profiles per run with `input.postRunHooks: [\"publish-d